<h2>Why the ONS and Home Office figures never match</h2>

<p>Two different organisations count two different things, and readers regularly set one
against the other as though the gap were a discrepancy. It is not.</p>

<div class="scroll-x">
<table>
  <caption>The two sources measure different quantities</caption>
  <thead><tr><th scope="col"></th><th scope="col">ONS migration estimates</th><th scope="col">Home Office visa statistics</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><th scope="row">Counts</th><td>People moving for 12 months or more</td><td>Visas granted</td></tr>
    <tr><th scope="row">Includes British citizens</th><td>Yes, arriving and leaving</td><td>No</td></tr>
    <tr><th scope="row">A grant that is never used</th><td>Not counted — no move happened</td><td>Counted</td></tr>
    <tr><th scope="row">Someone already in the UK extending</th><td>Not counted — no move happened</td><td>Counted</td></tr>
    <tr><th scope="row">Latest period</th><td>Year ending December 2025</td><td>Year ending March 2026</td></tr>
    <tr><th scope="row">Status</th><td>Official statistics in development, provisional</td><td>Accredited official statistics</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>
</div>

<p>The visa total will always be higher, and it is supposed to be. Neither figure is wrong;
they answer different questions.</p>

<h2>These estimates get revised</h2>

<p>Net migration for the year ending December 2024 was first published at 431,000, then at
about 345,000, and now stands at {% figure "migration/net-migration-2" %}. Nobody's movements changed —
the estimate did, as more travel data became available.</p>

<p>That is the statistics system working rather than failing, but it means any single figure
quoted from a past release may already be superseded. Each figure on this site carries the
date its source was published for exactly that reason.</p>

